      • isMigrationNeededForAndroidQ

        public boolean isMigrationNeededForAndroidQ​(String tokenName)
                                     throws IdpException
        Check if the migration is needed for Android Q with the given token name. If the migration is needed, app should ask the end user for the permission READ_PHONE_STATE and then call the migration API migrateForAndroidQ(String, byte[]).

        NOTE: This API should be called during the application startup to make sure that the permission popup, if any, will not interfere with other business flow.

        For more information on Android Q privacy changes, refer to https://developer.android.com/preview/privacy/data-identifiers#device-ids

        Parameters:
        tokenName - The token name.
        Returns:
        true if migration is needed, otherwise false.
        Throws:
        IdpStorageException - When database operation failed.
        PasswordManagerException - When the TOKEN domain is not logged in using the password manager.
        IdpException
        Since:
        4.9.2
        See Also:
        migrateForAndroidQ(String, byte[])

      • migrateForAndroidQ

        public void migrateForAndroidQ​(String tokenName,
                               byte[] customData)
                        throws IdpException
        Migrate the old token to be compatible with Android Q. In order to retrieve the old token, this API needs the READ_PHONE_STATE permission to be granted. After the migration, the permission is not required anymore.

        For more information on Android Q privacy changes, refer to https://developer.android.com/preview/privacy/data-identifiers#device-ids

        Parameters:
        tokenName - The name of the token to be migrated.
        customData - The custom data.
        Throws:
        IdpStorageException - When database operation failed.
        PasswordManagerException - When the TOKEN domain is not logged in using the password manager.
        DeviceFingerprintException - When the fingerprint data does not match.
        IdpException
        Since:
        4.9.2
        See Also:
        isMigrationNeededForAndroidQ(String)

      • updateDeviceFingerprintTokenPolicy

        public void updateDeviceFingerprintTokenPolicy​(@NonNull
                                               String tokenName,
                                               @Nullable
                                               byte[] oldCustomFingerprintData,
                                               @NonNull
                                               DeviceFingerprintTokenPolicy newTokenFingerprintPolicy)
                                        throws IdpException
        To apply the new device fingerprint policy to the token. This API will change (add or remove) the token policy properties such as:
        • The mode failIfInvalid (refer to DeviceFingerprintTokenPolicy(boolean, DeviceFingerprintSource))
        • The custom fingerprint data (refer to DeviceFingerprintSource(byte[], DeviceFingerprintSource.Type...)).

          NOTE: The application manages the custom fingerprint data value so that it uses the proper value while retrieving the token, for example, by calling CapTokenManager.getToken(String, byte[])

        • The fingerprint source type (refer to DeviceFingerprintSource.Type)

        NOTE: The application has to retrieve the token object again to update the changes, for example, by calling CapTokenManager.getToken(String) or CapTokenManager.getToken(String, byte[])

        Parameters:
        tokenName - The token name.
        oldCustomFingerprintData - The old custom fingerprint data (if any).
        newTokenFingerprintPolicy - The new token device fingerprint policy.
        Throws:
        IdpException - If the update fails. The possible errors are as follows:
        • IdpStorageException: Failed to retrieve the token information from internal database.
        • PasswordManagerException: The user has not logged in to PasswordManager.
        • DeviceFingerprintException: The provided oldCustomFingerprintData does not match with the one in token. Especially, the code IdpResultCode.FINGERPRINT_UPDATE_FAILED_IDENTICAL_POLICY will be thrown if the old and new policy are identical.
        • IdpException: A generic error. Check the code or message for more details.
        Since:
        5.4
        See Also:
        CapTokenManager.getToken(String), CapTokenManager.getToken(String, byte[]), OathTokenManager.getToken(String), OathTokenManager.getToken(String, byte[]), VicTokenManager.getToken(String), VicTokenManager.getToken(String, byte[])
